**b.)** For this, we will use the all-equity plan as the basis for the computations. In order to solve for the break-even EBIT, we will equate Plan I to the all-equity plan and do the same for Plan II and the all-equity plan.

For this, we will use the same formula we used for the EPS:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{EPS}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-(\text{Rate} \times \text{Debt})}{\text{Outstanding shares}}
\end{aligned}$$

For the EBIT between Plan I and the all-equity plan, we have:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-(0.10 \times \$109,250)}{12,700}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}}{15,000}
\end{aligned}$$

Cross multiply to remove the terms in the denominator:

$$\begin{aligned}
15,000 \times(\text{EBIT}-\$10,925)&=12,700 \times \text{EBIT}\\[15 pt]
15,000\text{EBIT}-\$163,875,000&=12,700\text{EBIT}
\end{aligned}$$

For Plan II, we will use the same concept:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-(0.10 \times \$247,000)}{9,800}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}}{15,000}
\end{aligned}$$

Cross multiply to remove the terms in the denominator:

$$\begin{aligned}
15,000 \times(\text{EBIT}-\$24,700)&=9,800 \times \text{EBIT}\\[15 pt]
15,000\text{EBIT}-\$370,500,000&=9,800\text{EBIT}
\end{aligned}$$

**c.)** For this, we will again equate the EPS for Plan I and Plan II to solve for the EBIT that will make their EPS equal to each other.

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-(0.10 \times \$109,250)}{12,700}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-(0.10 \times \$247,000)}{9,800}\\[15 pt]
\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-\$10,925}{12,700}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}-\$24,700}{9,800}
\end{aligned}$$

**d.)** For this, we will now use $21\%$ as the tax rate. We will use this formula to solve for the EPS:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{EPS}&=\dfrac{[\text{EBIT}-(\text{Interest rate} \times \text{Debt})] \times(1-\text{Tax rate})}{\text{Outstanding shares}}
\end{aligned}$$

From this, we will equate the EPS formula for Plan I and the all-equity plan and do the same for Plan II and all-equity plan.

For Plan I and all-equity:
$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{[\text{EBIT}-(0.10 \times \$109,250)]\times(1-0.21)}{12,700}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}\times(1-0.21)}{15,000}\\[15 pt]
\dfrac{0.79\text{EBIT}-\$8,630.75}{12,700}&=\dfrac{0.79\text{EBIT}}{15,000}
\end{aligned}$$

For Plan II and all-equity:
$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{[\text{EBIT}-(0.10 \times \$247,000)]\times(1-0.21)}{9,800}&=\dfrac{\text{EBIT}\times(1-0.21)}{15,000}\\[15 pt]
\dfrac{0.79\text{EBIT}-\$19,513}{9,800}&=\dfrac{0.79\text{EBIT}}{15,000}
\end{aligned}$$
